<p>

<b>Geoff Holt</b> (1942–1998) was a British artist. Born in London, Holt was active artistically from 1965–1998, first at <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../200/94200.xml">
Notting Hill</link></site>
 and later living and working in <county wordnetid="108546183" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../166/8166.xml">
Devon</link></county>
 until his death.</p>
<p>

Holt started his professional career in <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../867/93867.xml">
Bayswater</link></site>
 selling to tourists from the railings at <region wordnetid="108630985" confidence="0.8">
<area wordnetid="108497294" confidence="0.8">
<park wordnetid="108615149" confidence="0.8">
<location wordnetid="100027167" confidence="0.8">
<tract wordnetid="108673395" confidence="0.8">
<scene wordnetid="108645963" confidence="0.8">
<geographical_area wordnetid="108574314" confidence="0.8">
<venue wordnetid="108677628" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../289/211289.xml">
Hyde Park</link></venue>
</geographical_area>
</scene>
</tract>
</location>
</park>
</area>
</region>
. Thus his work spread worldwide; an example is the hand colored print "The Hunter", discovered and restored in <autocracy wordnetid="108361001" confidence="0.8">
<body wordnetid="107965085" confidence="0.8">
<social_group wordnetid="107950920" confidence="0.8">
